T1  - DEFINING QUALITY: ALTERNATIVES AND IMPLICATIONS
AU  - Reeves, Carol A.
AU  - Bednar, David A.
Y1  - 1994/07/01
PY  - 1994
DA  - 1994/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1994.9412271805
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1994.9412271805
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 419
EP  - 445
VL  - 19
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The search for a universal definition of quality has yielded inconsistent results. Such a global definition does not exist; rather, different definitions of quality are appropriate under different circumstances. In this article, we trace the evolution of quality definitions and describe the trade-offs inherent in accepting one definition of quality over another. The implications of using various definitions of quality in future research also are discussed.
AB  - The search for a universal definition of quality has yielded inconsistent results. Such a global definition does not exist; rather, different definitions of quality are appropriate under different circumstances. In this article, we trace the evolution of quality definitions and describe the trade-offs inherent in accepting one definition of quality over another. The implications of using various definitions of quality in future research also are discussed.
